ury Poznania and Jewish Relations with Poles and Germans / rMakowski, Krzysztof A. -- tBelgian Independence, Orangism, and Jewish Identity. The Jewish Communities in Belgium during the Belgian Revolution (1830-39) / rWallet, Bart -- tCitizenship, Regionalization, and Identity. The Case of Alsatian Jewry, 1871-1914 / rHyman, Paula E. -- tMoroccan Jewry and Decolonization. A Modern History of Collective Social Boundaries / rTsur, Yaron -- tContributors -- tIndex of Names and Places0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis study explores the shifting boundaries and identities of historic and contemporary Jewish communities. The contributors assert that, geographically speaking, Jewish people rarely lived in ghettos and have never been confined within the borders of one nation or country. Whereas their places of residence may have remained the same for centuries, the countries and regimes that ruled over them were rarely as constant, and power struggles often led to the creation of new and divisive national borders. Taking a postmodern historical approach, the contributors seek to reexamine Jewish history and Jewish studies through the lens of borders and boundaries.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aJewsvCongresses. 0aJewsxIdentityvCongresses. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aCahen, Joël, eeditor.1 aFrishman, Judith, eeditor.1 aWertheim, David J., eeditor.1 ade Haan, Ido, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAUP eBook Package Backlist 2002-2015z978311066278808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam Univ.Press  eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311060651540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048521494zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/cover